{"title_page": "Tom Yawkey", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = Tom Yawkey\n| image       =Tom Yawkey NYWTS.jpg\n| caption     = Tom Yawkey with his first wife Elise Sparrow Yawkey in 1938\n| birth_name  = Thomas Yawkey Austin\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1903|2|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1976|7|9|1903|2|21}}\n| death_place = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|hoflink = National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum\n|hoftype = National\n|hofdate=[[1980 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1980]]\n|hofmethod=Veterans Committee\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Austin Yawkey''', born '''Thomas Yawkey Austin''' (February 21, 1903 \u2013 July 9, 1976), was an American industrialist and [[Major League Baseball]] executive. Born in [[Detroit]], Yawkey became president of the [[Boston Red Sox]] in 1933 and was the sole owner of the team for 44 seasons, longer than anyone else in baseball history. He was elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in 1980. In 2018, the Red Sox publicly distanced themselves from Yawkey, due to allegations of racism and resistance to baseball's integration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/02/28/red-sox-ask-for-city-change-name-yawkey-way-back-jersey-street/0lPeEBY4rIKDXxKcQxBQ9M/story.html|title=Red Sox ask Boston to change name of Yawkey Way back to Jersey Street |first=Martin |last=Finucane |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=February 28, 2018 |access-date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nYawkey was born in Detroit on February 21, 1903 to [[insurance]] executive Thomas J. Austin and his wife Augusta. Augusta was the eldest child of William Clyman Yawkey, who had become wealthy in the [[lumber]] and [[iron ore]] industries of the [[Midwestern United States]].<ref name=\"SABR\" /> In addition to these interests, William Clyman Yawkey had agreed in principle to buy the [[Detroit Tigers]] baseball team in 1903, but he died before the deal closed. His son, [[Bill Yawkey]], eventually completed the purchase, though the younger Yawkey had little interest in the team and allowed team executive [[Frank Navin]] to control day-to-day operations and eventually purchase part of the team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/dba7471c|title=Frank Navin {{!}} Society for American Baseball Research|website=sabr.org|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref>\n\nShortly after Tom Yawkey's birth, his father, Thomas J. Austin, died. Tom, his mother, and his sister later went to live with Tom's uncle Bill Yawkey in [[New York City]]. After his mother died in 1918, Bill Yawkey and his wife [[Adoption|adopted]] him, and he took the Yawkey name.<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web |last=Armour|first=Mark |date= |title=Tom Yawkey |publisher=Society for American Baseball Research |url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/6382f9d5|access-date=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBill Yawkey died in 1919 and left his $40 million estate to his adopted son Tom, but a clause in the will forbade him from taking possession of it until he turned 30 years old. Tom Yawkey was a graduate of the [[Sheffield Scientific School]] at [[Yale University]] in 1925<ref name=\"SABR\" /> and was a member of the [[Phi Gamma Delta]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/6382f9d5 |title= Thomas A. Yawkey |publisher=Phi Gamma Delta |access-date=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Boston Red Sox==\nOn February 25, 1933, four days after his 30th birthday, Yawkey bought the Red Sox for $1.25 million, and persuaded friend and former [[Philadelphia Athletics]] second baseman [[Eddie Collins]] to be the team's vice president and general manager.<ref name=SABR />\n\nThe Red Sox had been the dregs of the [[American League]] for more than a decade following the infamous [[Babe Ruth]] sale to the [[New York Yankees]] by former owner [[Harry Frazee]] before the 1920 season,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Armour|first1=Mark |last2=Levitt |first2=Daniel |last3=Levitt |first3=Matthew |date=2008 |title=Harry Frazee and the Red Sox |publisher=Society for American Baseball Research |url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/harry-frazee-and-the-red-sox |access-date=January 14, 2017}}</ref> and had just finished the [[1932 Boston Red Sox season|1932 season]] with a record of {{Winning percentage|43|111|record=y}}\u2014still the worst in franchise history.<ref name=\"Baseball-Reference.com\">{{cite web |title=Boston Red Sox Team History & Encyclopedia |website=Baseball-Reference.com |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/BOS/ |access-date=January 14, 2017}}</ref> Yawkey directed Collins to buy up as much talent as possible to turn the team around.<ref>{{cite book |last=Golenbock |first=Peter |date=2015 |title=Red Sox Nation: The Rich and Colorful History of the Boston Red Sox |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ggPooQEACAAJ&dq=red+sox+nation+peter+golenbock&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiCoqWvo7DRAhWi6oMKHfewBHYQ6AEIHDAA |location=Chicago, Ill. |publisher=Triumph Books LLC |pages=88\u201391 |isbn=978-1-62937-050-7}}</ref> He also heavily renovated [[Fenway Park]], which had fallen into disrepair over the years.<ref>{{cite book |last=Golenbock |first=Peter |date=2015 |title=Red Sox Nation: The Rich and Colorful History of the Boston Red Sox |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ggPooQEACAAJ&dq=red+sox+nation+peter+golenbock&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiCoqWvo7DRAhWi6oMKHfewBHYQ6AEIHDAA |location=Chicago, Ill. |publisher=Triumph Books LLC |page=90 |isbn=978-1-62937-050-7}}</ref>\n\nYawkey devoted his time and finances for the rest of his life to attempting to build winning teams,<ref name=SABR /> with ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' citing Yawkey's estimation in 1974 that he lost $10 million on the team during his tenure owning the Red Sox.<ref name=driscoll>{{cite news |last=Driscoll |first=Edgar J. |date=1976-07-10 |title=Tom Yawkey, Red Sox owner, dies at 73 |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/1976/07/10/tom-yawkey-red-sox-owner-dies/HnDKMujvXmmjzT71xfMSmK/story.html |url-status=live |newspaper=The Boston Globe |access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref> His teams' best seasons took place in 1946, 1967, and 1975, when the Red Sox captured the [[List of American League pennant winners|American League pennant]] but then went on to lose each [[World Series]] in seven games, against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] ([[1946 World Series|1946]], [[1967 World Series|1967]]) and the [[Cincinnati Reds]] ([[1975 World Series|1975]]). He would never achieve his ultimate goal of winning a world championship.<ref name=Baseball-Reference.com />\n\n===Criticism and controversies===\nThe [[Baseball color line#Resistance by the Boston Red Sox|resistance to signing black players]] by the Red Sox, who were the last major league team to integrate, has led to assertions of Yawkey being racist.<ref name=shutout /> The Red Sox had multiple black players in their farm system during the 1950s, with the team failing to promote them despite the successes other teams realized after integrating black players.<ref>{{cite book |last=Golenbock |first=Peter |date=2015 |title=Red Sox Nation: The Rich and Colorful History of the Boston Red Sox |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ggPooQEACAAJ&dq=red+sox+nation+peter+golenbock&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiCoqWvo7DRAhWi6oMKHfewBHYQ6AEIHDAA |location=Chicago, Ill. |publisher=Triumph Books LLC |pages=224\u2013229 |isbn=978-1-62937-050-7}}</ref> During this period, the Red Sox went from perennial contender to failing to finish within ten games of first place for 16 years (1951\u20131966).<ref name=Baseball-Reference.com /> As owner of the Boston Red Sox, the team's policy on integration ultimately was Yawkey's responsibility.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bryant |first=Howard |date=September 2, 2003 |title=Shut Out: A Story of Race and Baseball in Boston |url=https://archive.org/details/shutoutstoryofra00brya/page/40 |location= |publisher=Beacon Press |page=40 |isbn=978-0807009796 |url-access=registration }}</ref> In [[1959 Boston Red Sox season|1959]], the Red Sox became the last major league team to field a black player, [[Pumpsie Green]], twelve years after [[Jackie Robinson]]'s rookie season with the [[1947 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]] and two-and-a-half years after Robinson's retirement. Robinson would later call Yawkey \"one of the most bigoted guys in baseball\".<ref name=shutout>{{cite book |last=Bryant |first=Howard |date=September 2, 2003 |title=Shut Out: A Story of Race and Baseball in Boston |url=https://archive.org/details/shutoutstoryofra00brya/page/88 |location= |publisher=Beacon Press |page=88 |isbn=978-0807009796 |url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nAnother controversy involved longtime clubhouse attendant Donald Fitzpatrick. Fitzpatrick was accused of [[sexual abuse of minors]] between 1971 and 1991 while working in the Red Sox spring training clubhouse in [[Winter Haven, Florida]].<ref name=Passan/> The abuse was reported to the team by victims and players who witnessed it, but Fitzpatrick remained employed.<ref name=Passan/> Yawkey, and later his wife Jean after Tom's death, protected Fitzpatrick from the allegations, according to two sources with knowledge of their relationship.<ref name=Passan/> During Fitzpatrick's time in the organization, Red Sox players allegedly warned young boys, especially those who were African-American, to not spend time with Fitzpatrick.<ref name=Passan/> Fitzpatrick would continue as Red Sox clubhouse attendant for 15 years after Tom Yawkey\u2019s death.<ref name=Passan/>\u00a0 \n\nIn 1991, Fitzpatrick ended his role in the organization after a man brought a sign to a game in [[Anaheim, California]], that read \u201cDonald Fitzpatrick Sexually Assaulted Me\u201d.<ref name=Passan/> The man, whose identity is unknown to this day, held the sign over the Red Sox dugout as [[batting practice]] was ending.<ref name=Passan/> Four days after the incident, Fitzpatrick departed from the organization and never rejoined the team in any capacity.<ref name=Passan/>\n\nIn 2001, seven former Red Sox clubhouse attendants sued the organization for $3.15 million over Fitzpatrick\u2019s alleged sexual abuse.<ref name=Toll>{{Cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2012/10/01/toll-of-accusers-in-red-sox-abuse-case-grows |title=Toll of accusers in Red Sox abuse case grows |website=[[Boston.com]] |first=Bob |last=Hohler |date=October 1, 2012 |access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> After [[John W. Henry]] and his partners bought the team in 2002, they took on all aspects of the Boston Red Sox, which included this lawsuit.<ref name=Toll/> The new ownership group ended the lawsuit by settling with Fitzpatrick\u2019s alleged victims.<ref name=Toll/> They paid these seven alleged victims of Fitzpatrick in a multi-million dollar settlement.<ref name=Toll/>\n\nIn 2002, Fitzpatrick pleaded guilty after being charged with four counts of attempted [[sexual battery]] for actions between 1975 and 1989.<ref name=Passan>{{cite web |last=Passan |first=Jeff |url=http://www.thepostgame.com/features/201111/another-era-and-another-sport-sex-abuse-scandal-still-inflicting-pain-today |title=From Another Era And Another Sport, A Sex Abuse Scandal Still Inflicting Pain Today  |date=November 10, 2011 |website=ThePostGame}}</ref> As part of the plea deal, the 72-year-old Fitzpatrick would not have to serve jail time.<ref name=Passan/> He was given a 10-year suspended sentence and 15 years of probation.<ref name=Passan/> Fitzpatrick was never sent to prison during this sentence and died in 2005 at the age of 76.<ref name=Toll/>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[Image:Fenway Park01.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Fenway Park]] main entrance on the then [[Yawkey Way]] in 2007]]\nYawkey was a popular figure in Boston and a respected voice in major league councils, as evidenced<ref name=SABR /> by his fellow American League owners naming him vice president between 1956 and 1973,<ref name=YFbio>{{cite web |url=http://yawkeyfoundation.org/thomas_yawkey.html |title=Thomas A. Yawkey |website=yawkeyfoundation.org |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> though fellow owners regarded him as a \"strange fish\" in the words of one contemporary sports writer for Yawkey's willingness to spend lavishly on salaries and perks for star players at the expense of profits.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/12/archives/man-who-couldnt-buy-pennants.html?_r=0 |title=Man Who Couldn't Buy Pennants |newspaper=The New York Times |date=July 12, 1976 |accessdate=January 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYawkey died from [[leukemia]] in [[Boston]] on July 9, 1976.<ref name=SABR /> His wife, [[Jean R. Yawkey]], became president of the club following his death. The Yawkey Foundation was established in 1976 through a bequest in his will. The foundation later recorded $420 million in 2002 income after the sale of the Red Sox. Alongside a second foundation formed in 1982 by Jean Yawkey, the Yawkey Foundations donated $30 million in 2007 for the [[Dana\u2013Farber Cancer Institute]] to build the Yawkey Center for Cancer Care in Boston.<ref name=SABR />\n\nIn 1977, the section of Jersey Street where [[Fenway Park]] is located was renamed [[Yawkey Way]] in his honor. However, in August 2017, Red Sox principal owner [[John W. Henry]] announced the team was seeking to change the name, adding he was \"haunted\" by Yawkey's legacy, which some have characterized as racist.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2017/08/18/haunted-by-past-owners-history-red-sox-seek-name-change-for-yawkey-way/ |title='Haunted' by past owner's history, Red Sox seek name change for Yawkey Way |newspaper=Boston Herald |date=August 18, 2017 |accessdate=March 29, 2018}}</ref> The change was approved by the City of Boston in April 2018, and the name reverted to Jersey Street in May 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2018/05/03/yawkey-way-signs-come-down-outside-fenway-park |title=Yawkey Way signs come down outside Fenway Park |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=May 3, 2018 |accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref> A plaque honoring Yawkey, from \"his Red Sox employees,\" that had hung at the administrative office entrance to Fenway Park since shortly after his death was removed in May 2018.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://commonwealthmagazine.org/arts-and-culture/a-missing-pair-of-sox/ |title=A missing pair of Sox |first=Jack |last=Sullivan |magazine=[[CommonWealth Magazine|CommonWealth]] |date=May 21, 2018 |accessdate=May 24, 2018}}</ref> An [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] station near the park, Yawkey station, was renamed [[Lansdowne station (MBTA)|Lansdowne station]] in April 2019.  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2019/03/28/yawkey-station-is-now-lansdowne-station | title=The MBTA is renaming Yawkey Station after another nearby street |publisher=Boston Globe |website=[[Boston.com]]|date=March 29, 2019 |accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA chain of islands off the coast of [[Georgetown, South Carolina]], near the entrance of [[Winyah Bay]], make up the Tom Yawkey Wildlife Center Heritage Preserve. The nature preserve was formed from 24,000 acres of land along a tidal estuary, which Yawkey willed to the South Carolina Department of Natural Resources. He originally purchased the land for use as a hunting and fishing retreat, and often allowed access to Red Sox players, including [[Ted Williams]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.postandcourier.com/archives/link-to-a-jewel/article_37ca6e42-5ad5-5a3a-b167-d24dd9e76d0c.html |title=Link to 'a jewel' |publisher=The Post & Courier |date=December 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref> It consists of North Island, South Island, Sand Island <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zinsser|first1=Elizabeth|title=NEST SUCCESS AND HABITAT CHOICE OF WILSON'S PLOVERS IN TOM YAWKEY WILDLIFE CENTER HERITAGE PRESERVE, SOUTH CAROLINA|journal=All Theses|date=2013|url=https://tigerprints.clemson.edu/all_theses/1937/|accessdate=30 December 2017}}</ref> and a majority of Cat Island.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.audubon.org/important-bird-areas/tom-yawkey-wildlife-center |title=Tom Yawkey Wildlife Center |publisher=Audubon |accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYawkey was elected to the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Baseball Hall of Fame]] in 1980.<ref name=HOF>{{cite web |url=http://baseballhall.org/hof/yawkey-tom |title=Tom Yawkey |website=The Baseball Hall of Fame |accessdate=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nYawkey married Elise Sparrow in 1925,<ref name=\"Jean R. Yawkey\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/27/sports/jean-r-yawkey-red-sox-owner-and-philanthropist-is-dead-at-83.html |title=Jean R. Yawkey, Red Sox Owner And Philanthropist, Is Dead at 83 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 27, 1992 |accessdate=January 14, 2017 |first=Robert McG. |last=Thomas Jr. |authorlink=Robert McG. Thomas Jr.}}</ref> with the couple adopting a daughter named Julia in 1936. With different interests, the couple would drift apart and divorce in November 1944. Both remarried within a few weeks of the divorce, Tom Yawkey to department store model [[Jean R. Yawkey|Jean R. Hiller]]. Tom and Jean Yawkey had no children.<ref name=SABR />\n\nYawkey's friends addressed him as \"T.A.\"; he was fond of taking batting practice at Fenway Park, exulting when hitting a ball off the [[Green Monster]] left field wall.<ref name=driscoll/>\n\nThe only full-length biography of Yawkey is entitled ''Tom Yawkey: Patriarch of the Boston Red Sox''. It was written by Bill Nowlin and was published by the [[University of Nebraska Press]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/review-tom-yawkey-a-stain-on-red-sox-nation-1517608976 |title=Review: 'Tom Yawkey' and the Red Sox' 'Original Sin' |first=Leigh |last=Montville |authorlink=Leigh Montville |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=February 2, 2018 |quote=Boston was an all-white ball club until 1959\u201412 years after Jackie Robinson became a Dodger.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame]]\n*''[[The Victory Season]]'', a book about the 1946 baseball season\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |title=Tom Yawkey: Patriarch of the Boston Red Sox |first=Bill |last=Nowlin |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |date=2018 |isbn=0803296835 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Tom-Yawkey-Patriarch-Boston-Red/dp/0803296835/}}\n* {{cite magazine |title=Milestones, Jan. 8, 1945 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,775353,00.html |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=January 8, 1945 |quote=Married. Thomas Austin Yawkey}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{bbhof|yawkey-tom}}\n*{{findagrave|5860754}}\n*[http://www.yawkeyfoundation.org Yawkey Foundation]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Bob Quinn (baseball)|J. A. Robert Quinn]]\n| title=Owner of the [[Boston Red Sox]]\n| years=February 25, 1933 \u2013 July 9, 1976\n| after=[[Jean R. Yawkey]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Boston Red Sox}}\n{{1980 Baseball HOF}}\n{{Baseball Hall of Fame members}}\n{{Boston Red Sox owners}}\n{{Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yawkey, Tom}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox executives]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox owners]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Deaths from leukemia]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball executives]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball owners]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball team presidents]]\n[[Category:National Baseball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Engineering & Applied Science alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = Tom Yawkey\n| image       =Tom Yawkey NYWTS.jpg\n| caption     = Tom Yawkey with his first wife Elise Sparrow Yawkey in 1938\n| birth_name  = Thomas Yawkey Austin\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1903|2|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1976|7|9|1903|2|21}}\n| death_place = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|hoflink = National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum\n|hoftype = National\n|hofdate=[[1980 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1980]]\n|hofmethod=Veterans Committee\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Austin Yawkey''', born '''Thomas Yawkey Austin''' (February 21, 1903 \u2013 July 9, 1976), was an American industrialist and [[Major League Baseball]] executive. Born in [[Detroit]], Yawkey became president of the [[Boston Red Sox]] in 1933 and was the sole owner of the team for 44 seasons, longer than anyone else in baseball history. He was elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in 1980. In 2018, the Red Sox publicly distanced themselves from Yawkey, due to allegations of racism and resistance to baseball's integration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/02/28/red-sox-ask-for-city-change-name-yawkey-way-back-jersey-street/0lPeEBY4rIKDXxKcQxBQ9M/story.html|title=Red Sox ask Boston to change name of Yawkey Way back to Jersey Street |first=Martin |last=Finucane |website=[[The Boston Globe]] |url-access=limited |date=February 28, 2018 |access-date=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nYawkey was born in Detroit on February 21, 1903 to [[insurance]] executive Thomas J. Austin and his wife Augusta. Augusta was the eldest child of William Clyman Yawkey, who had become wealthy in the [[lumber]] and [[iron ore]] industries of the [[Midwestern United States]].<ref name=\"SABR\" /> In addition to these interests, William Clyman Yawkey had agreed in principle to buy the [[Detroit Tigers]] baseball team in 1903, but he died before the deal closed. His son, [[Bill Yawkey]], eventually completed the purchase, though the younger Yawkey had little interest in the team and allowed team executive [[Frank Navin]] to control day-to-day operations and eventually purchase part of the team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/dba7471c|title=Frank Navin {{!}} Society for American Baseball Research|website=sabr.org|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref>\n\nShortly after Tom Yawkey's birth, his father, Thomas J. Austin, died. Tom, his mother, and his sister later went to live with Tom's uncle Bill Yawkey in [[New York City]]. After his mother died in 1918, Bill Yawkey and his wife [[Adoption|adopted]] him, and he took the Yawkey name.<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web |last=Armour|first=Mark |date= |title=Tom Yawkey |publisher=Society for American Baseball Research |url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/6382f9d5|access-date=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBill Yawkey died in 1919 and left his $40 million estate to his adopted son Tom, but a clause in the will forbade him from taking possession of it until he turned 30 years old. Tom Yawkey was a graduate of the [[Sheffield Scientific School]] at [[Yale University]] in 1925<ref name=\"SABR\" /> and was a member of the [[Phi Gamma Delta]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/6382f9d5 |title= Thomas A. Yawkey |publisher=Phi Gamma Delta |access-date=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Boston Red Sox==\nOn February 25, 1933, four days after his 30th birthday, Yawkey bought the Red Sox for $1.25 million, and persuaded friend and former [[Philadelphia Athletics]] second baseman [[Eddie Collins]] to be the team's vice president and general manager.<ref name=SABR />\n\nThe Red Sox had been the dregs of the [[American League]] for more than a decade following the infamous [[Babe Ruth]] sale to the [[New York Yankees]] by former owner [[Harry Frazee]] before the 1920 season,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Armour|first1=Mark |last2=Levitt |first2=Daniel |last3=Levitt |first3=Matthew |date=2008 |title=Harry Frazee and the Red Sox |publisher=Society for American Baseball Research |url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/harry-frazee-and-the-red-sox |access-date=January 14, 2017}}</ref> and had just finished the [[1932 Boston Red Sox season|1932 season]] with a record of {{Winning percentage|43|111|record=y}}\u2014still the worst in franchise history.<ref name=\"Baseball-Reference.com\">{{cite web |title=Boston Red Sox Team History & Encyclopedia |website=Baseball-Reference.com |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/BOS/ |access-date=January 14, 2017}}</ref> Yawkey directed Collins to buy up as much talent as possible to turn the team around.<ref>{{cite book |last=Golenbock |first=Peter |date=2015 |title=Red Sox Nation: The Rich and Colorful History of the Boston Red Sox |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ggPooQEACAAJ&dq=red+sox+nation+peter+golenbock&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiCoqWvo7DRAhWi6oMKHfewBHYQ6AEIHDAA |location=Chicago, Ill. |publisher=Triumph Books LLC |pages=88\u201391 |isbn=978-1-62937-050-7}}</ref> He also heavily renovated [[Fenway Park]], which had fallen into disrepair over the years.<ref>{{cite book |last=Golenbock |first=Peter |date=2015 |title=Red Sox Nation: The Rich and Colorful History of the Boston Red Sox |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ggPooQEACAAJ&dq=red+sox+nation+peter+golenbock&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiCoqWvo7DRAhWi6oMKHfewBHYQ6AEIHDAA |location=Chicago, Ill. |publisher=Triumph Books LLC |page=90 |isbn=978-1-62937-050-7}}</ref>\n\nYawkey devoted his time and finances for the rest of his life to attempting to build winning teams,<ref name=SABR /> with ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' citing Yawkey's estimation in 1974 that he lost $10 million on the team during his tenure owning the Red Sox.<ref name=driscoll>{{cite news |last=Driscoll |first=Edgar J. |date=1976-07-10 |title=Tom Yawkey, Red Sox owner, dies at 73 |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/1976/07/10/tom-yawkey-red-sox-owner-dies/HnDKMujvXmmjzT71xfMSmK/story.html |url-status=live |newspaper=The Boston Globe |access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref> His teams' best seasons took place in 1946, 1967, and 1975, when the Red Sox captured the [[List of American League pennant winners|American League pennant]] but then went on to lose each [[World Series]] in seven games, against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] ([[1946 World Series|1946]], [[1967 World Series|1967]]) and the [[Cincinnati Reds]] ([[1975 World Series|1975]]). He would never achieve his ultimate goal of winning a world championship.<ref name=Baseball-Reference.com />\n\n===Criticism and controversies===\nThe [[Baseball color line#Resistance by the Boston Red Sox|resistance to signing black players]] by the Red Sox, who were the last major league team to integrate, has led to assertions of Yawkey being racist.<ref name=shutout /> The Red Sox had multiple black players in their farm system during the 1950s, with the team failing to promote them despite the successes other teams realized after integrating black players.<ref>{{cite book |last=Golenbock |first=Peter |date=2015 |title=Red Sox Nation: The Rich and Colorful History of the Boston Red Sox |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ggPooQEACAAJ&dq=red+sox+nation+peter+golenbock&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiCoqWvo7DRAhWi6oMKHfewBHYQ6AEIHDAA |location=Chicago, Ill. |publisher=Triumph Books LLC |pages=224\u2013229 |isbn=978-1-62937-050-7}}</ref> During this period, the Red Sox went from perennial contender to failing to finish within ten games of first place for 16 years (1951\u20131966).<ref name=Baseball-Reference.com /> As owner of the Boston Red Sox, the team's policy on integration ultimately was Yawkey's responsibility.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bryant |first=Howard |date=September 2, 2003 |title=Shut Out: A Story of Race and Baseball in Boston |url=https://archive.org/details/shutoutstoryofra00brya/page/40 |location= |publisher=Beacon Press |page=40 |isbn=978-0807009796 |url-access=registration }}</ref> In [[1959 Boston Red Sox season|1959]], the Red Sox became the last major league team to field a black player, [[Pumpsie Green]], twelve years after [[Jackie Robinson]]'s rookie season with the [[1947 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]] and two-and-a-half years after Robinson's retirement. Robinson would later call Yawkey \"one of the most bigoted guys in baseball\".<ref name=shutout>{{cite book |last=Bryant |first=Howard |date=September 2, 2003 |title=Shut Out: A Story of Race and Baseball in Boston |url=https://archive.org/details/shutoutstoryofra00brya/page/88 |location= |publisher=Beacon Press |page=88 |isbn=978-0807009796 |url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nAnother controversy involved longtime clubhouse attendant Donald Fitzpatrick. Fitzpatrick was accused of [[sexual abuse of minors]] between 1971 and 1991 while working in the Red Sox spring training clubhouse in [[Winter Haven, Florida]].<ref name=sully /> The abuse was reported to the team by victims and players who witnessed it, but Fitzpatrick remained employed.<ref name=sully /> Yawkey, and later his wife Jean after Tom's death, protected Fitzpatrick from the allegations, according to two sources with knowledge of their relationship.<ref name=sully /> During Fitzpatrick's time in the organization, Red Sox players allegedly warned young boys, especially those who were African-American, to not spend time with Fitzpatrick.<ref name=Passan/> Fitzpatrick would continue as Red Sox clubhouse attendant for 15 years after Tom Yawkey\u2019s death.<ref name=Passan/>\u00a0 \n\nIn 1991, Fitzpatrick ended his role in the organization after a man brought a sign to a game in [[Anaheim, California]], that read \u201cDonald Fitzpatrick Sexually Assaulted Me\u201d.<ref name=Passan/> The man, whose identity is unknown to this day, held the sign over the Red Sox dugout as [[batting practice]] was ending.<ref name=Passan/> Four days after the incident, Fitzpatrick departed from the organization and never rejoined the team in any capacity.<ref name=Passan/>\n\nIn 2001, seven former Red Sox clubhouse attendants sued the organization for $3.15 million over Fitzpatrick\u2019s alleged sexual abuse.<ref name=Toll>{{Cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2012/10/01/toll-of-accusers-in-red-sox-abuse-case-grows |title=Toll of accusers in Red Sox abuse case grows |website=[[Boston.com]] |first=Bob |last=Hohler |date=October 1, 2012 |access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> After [[John W. Henry]] and his partners bought the team in 2002, they took on all aspects of the Boston Red Sox, which included this lawsuit.<ref name=Toll/> The new ownership group ended the lawsuit by settling with Fitzpatrick\u2019s alleged victims.<ref name=Toll/> They paid these seven alleged victims of Fitzpatrick in a multi-million dollar settlement.<ref name=Toll/>\n\nIn 2002, Fitzpatrick pleaded guilty after being charged with four counts of attempted [[sexual battery]] for actions between 1975 and 1989.<ref name=Passan>{{cite web |last=Passan |first=Jeff |url=http://www.thepostgame.com/features/201111/another-era-and-another-sport-sex-abuse-scandal-still-inflicting-pain-today |title=From Another Era And Another Sport, A Sex Abuse Scandal Still Inflicting Pain Today  |date=November 10, 2011 |website=ThePostGame}}</ref> As part of the plea deal, the 72-year-old Fitzpatrick would not have to serve jail time.<ref name=Passan/> He was given a 10-year suspended sentence and 15 years of probation.<ref name=Passan/> Fitzpatrick was never sent to prison during this sentence and died in 2005 at the age of 76.<ref name=Toll/>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[Image:Fenway Park01.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Fenway Park]] main entrance on the then [[Yawkey Way]] in 2007]]\nYawkey was a popular figure in Boston and a respected voice in major league councils, as evidenced<ref name=SABR /> by his fellow American League owners naming him vice president between 1956 and 1973,<ref name=YFbio>{{cite web |url=http://yawkeyfoundation.org/thomas_yawkey.html |title=Thomas A. Yawkey |website=yawkeyfoundation.org |accessdate=December 10, 2016}}</ref> though fellow owners regarded him as a \"strange fish\" in the words of one contemporary sports writer for Yawkey's willingness to spend lavishly on salaries and perks for star players at the expense of profits.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/12/archives/man-who-couldnt-buy-pennants.html?_r=0 |title=Man Who Couldn't Buy Pennants |newspaper=The New York Times |date=July 12, 1976 |accessdate=January 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYawkey died from [[leukemia]] in [[Boston]] on July 9, 1976.<ref name=SABR /> His wife, [[Jean R. Yawkey]], became president of the club following his death. The Yawkey Foundation was established in 1976 through a bequest in his will. The foundation later recorded $420 million in 2002 income after the sale of the Red Sox. Alongside a second foundation formed in 1982 by Jean Yawkey, the Yawkey Foundations donated $30 million in 2007 for the [[Dana\u2013Farber Cancer Institute]] to build the Yawkey Center for Cancer Care in Boston.<ref name=SABR />\n\nIn 1977, the section of Jersey Street where [[Fenway Park]] is located was renamed [[Yawkey Way]] in his honor. However, in August 2017, Red Sox principal owner [[John W. Henry]] announced the team was seeking to change the name, adding he was \"haunted\" by Yawkey's legacy, which some have characterized as racist.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2017/08/18/haunted-by-past-owners-history-red-sox-seek-name-change-for-yawkey-way/ |title='Haunted' by past owner's history, Red Sox seek name change for Yawkey Way |newspaper=Boston Herald |date=August 18, 2017 |accessdate=March 29, 2018}}</ref> The change was approved by the City of Boston in April 2018, and the name reverted to Jersey Street in May 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2018/05/03/yawkey-way-signs-come-down-outside-fenway-park |title=Yawkey Way signs come down outside Fenway Park |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=May 3, 2018 |accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref> A plaque honoring Yawkey, from \"his Red Sox employees,\" that had hung at the administrative office entrance to Fenway Park since shortly after his death was removed in May 2018.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://commonwealthmagazine.org/arts-and-culture/a-missing-pair-of-sox/ |title=A missing pair of Sox |first=Jack |last=Sullivan |magazine=[[CommonWealth Magazine|CommonWealth]] |date=May 21, 2018 |accessdate=May 24, 2018}}</ref> An [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] station near the park, Yawkey station, was renamed [[Lansdowne station (MBTA)|Lansdowne station]] in April 2019.  <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2019/03/28/yawkey-station-is-now-lansdowne-station | title=The MBTA is renaming Yawkey Station after another nearby street |publisher=Boston Globe |website=[[Boston.com]]|date=March 29, 2019 |accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA chain of islands off the coast of [[Georgetown, South Carolina]], near the entrance of [[Winyah Bay]], make up the Tom Yawkey Wildlife Center Heritage Preserve. The nature preserve was formed from 24,000 acres of land along a tidal estuary, which Yawkey willed to the South Carolina Department of Natural Resources. He originally purchased the land for use as a hunting and fishing retreat, and often allowed access to Red Sox players, including [[Ted Williams]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.postandcourier.com/archives/link-to-a-jewel/article_37ca6e42-5ad5-5a3a-b167-d24dd9e76d0c.html |title=Link to 'a jewel' |publisher=The Post & Courier |date=December 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref> It consists of North Island, South Island, Sand Island <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zinsser|first1=Elizabeth|title=NEST SUCCESS AND HABITAT CHOICE OF WILSON'S PLOVERS IN TOM YAWKEY WILDLIFE CENTER HERITAGE PRESERVE, SOUTH CAROLINA|journal=All Theses|date=2013|url=https://tigerprints.clemson.edu/all_theses/1937/|accessdate=30 December 2017}}</ref> and a majority of Cat Island.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.audubon.org/important-bird-areas/tom-yawkey-wildlife-center |title=Tom Yawkey Wildlife Center |publisher=Audubon |accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYawkey was elected to the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Baseball Hall of Fame]] in 1980.<ref name=HOF>{{cite web |url=http://baseballhall.org/hof/yawkey-tom |title=Tom Yawkey |website=The Baseball Hall of Fame |accessdate=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nYawkey married Elise Sparrow in 1925,<ref name=\"Jean R. Yawkey\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/27/sports/jean-r-yawkey-red-sox-owner-and-philanthropist-is-dead-at-83.html |title=Jean R. Yawkey, Red Sox Owner And Philanthropist, Is Dead at 83 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 27, 1992 |accessdate=January 14, 2017 |first=Robert McG. |last=Thomas Jr. |authorlink=Robert McG. Thomas Jr.}}</ref> with the couple adopting a daughter named Julia in 1936. With different interests, the couple would drift apart and divorce in November 1944. Both remarried within a few weeks of the divorce, Tom Yawkey to department store model [[Jean R. Yawkey|Jean R. Hiller]]. Tom and Jean Yawkey had no children.<ref name=SABR />\n\nYawkey's friends addressed him as \"T.A.\"; he was fond of taking batting practice at Fenway Park, exulting when hitting a ball off the [[Green Monster]] left field wall.<ref name=driscoll/>\n\nThe only full-length biography of Yawkey is entitled ''Tom Yawkey: Patriarch of the Boston Red Sox''. It was written by Bill Nowlin and was published by the [[University of Nebraska Press]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/review-tom-yawkey-a-stain-on-red-sox-nation-1517608976 |title=Review: 'Tom Yawkey' and the Red Sox' 'Original Sin' |first=Leigh |last=Montville |authorlink=Leigh Montville |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=February 2, 2018 |quote=Boston was an all-white ball club until 1959\u201412 years after Jackie Robinson became a Dodger.}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame]]\n*''[[The Victory Season]]'', a book about the 1946 baseball season\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |title=Tom Yawkey: Patriarch of the Boston Red Sox |first=Bill |last=Nowlin |publisher=University of Nebraska Press |date=2018 |isbn=0803296835 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Tom-Yawkey-Patriarch-Boston-Red/dp/0803296835/}}\n* {{cite magazine |title=Milestones, Jan. 8, 1945 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,775353,00.html |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=January 8, 1945 |quote=Married. Thomas Austin Yawkey}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{bbhof|yawkey-tom}}\n*{{findagrave|5860754}}\n*[http://www.yawkeyfoundation.org Yawkey Foundation]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Bob Quinn (baseball)|J. A. Robert Quinn]]\n| title=Owner of the [[Boston Red Sox]]\n| years=February 25, 1933 \u2013 July 9, 1976\n| after=[[Jean R. Yawkey]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Boston Red Sox}}\n{{1980 Baseball HOF}}\n{{Baseball Hall of Fame members}}\n{{Boston Red Sox owners}}\n{{Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yawkey, Tom}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox executives]]\n[[Category:Boston Red Sox owners]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Deaths from leukemia]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball executives]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball owners]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball team presidents]]\n[[Category:National Baseball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Engineering & Applied Science alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Dmoore5556", "label": "safe", "comment": "citation name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Yawkey"}
